                            <div class="accordion" data-accordion>
                                <div class="accordion-title" data-control>
                                    <span></span>
                                    <p>What is On Grid system?  </p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="accordion-content animated" data-content>
                                    <div class="content-inner">
                                        <p>An on-grid solar system, also known as a grid-tied or grid-connected solar system, is a renewable energy setup that allows you to generate electricity using solar panels and feed any excess power back into the utility grid. This means your solar installation is connected to the local electricity grid, functioning in tandem with the traditional power infrastructure.

How does an on-grid solar system work?

Solar Panels: At the heart of the on-grid solar system are photovoltaic (PV) solar panels. These panels contain solar cells that convert sunlight into direct current (DC) electricity. They are typically installed on rooftops, open fields, or any unobstructed areas where they can receive maximum sunlight exposure.

Inverter: The DC electricity generated by the solar panels cannot be directly used in most household appliances and electronics, which operate on alternating current (AC). That's where the inverter comes in. The inverter converts the DC electricity into AC electricity, making it compatible with your home's electrical system.

Power Meter: An additional or upgraded power meter is installed to monitor both the electricity consumed from the grid and the surplus electricity your solar system exports to the grid. This helps keep track of your energy usage and any credits or payments you may receive for the surplus electricity you contribute.

Interaction with the Grid: During sunny periods when your solar panels produce more electricity than your home needs, the excess power is sent back to the grid. In many regions, this surplus electricity is credited to your account, effectively "spinning your meter backward." This process is known as net metering or feed-in-tariff, depending on your location and local regulations.

Electricity from the Grid: When your solar panels are not producing enough electricity to meet your needs (e.g., during cloudy days or at night), you can draw power from the grid as usual. The electricity from the grid acts as a backup, ensuring a constant and reliable power supply.

Benefits of On-Grid Solar Systems:

Cost Savings: By generating your own electricity, you reduce your dependence on the grid, leading to lower electricity bills. Additionally, some regions offer incentives or tax credits for installing solar systems, making the initial investment even more attractive.

Environmental Impact: On-grid solar systems produce clean, renewable energy, significantly reducing greenhouse gas emissions and helping combat climate change. They contribute to a greener and more sustainable future.

Grid Stability: On-grid solar systems can contribute to the overall stability of the electricity grid. When numerous homes and businesses generate solar power, it lessens the strain on the grid during peak demand periods.

Minimal Maintenance: Solar panels have a long lifespan and generally require little maintenance, resulting in hassle-free ownership.

It's important to note that on-grid solar systems do not provide power during grid outages for safety reasons. To have backup power during emergencies, an additional energy storage system like batteries can be incorporated into the setup.

If you're considering embracing solar energy and making the most of the abundant sunlight available, an on-grid solar system could be an ideal choice for you. Reach out to our experts to explore your options and take a step towards a brighter and cleaner future with solar power!</p>
